Question: How do you believe ACME should better support organizations and cultural leaders?

Response ID: resp_4234
Response Text: What the City of Austin has done in the past 4-5 years has been astounding for marginalized and lesser represented arts groups. The tact, time and research that went into efforts to equalize funding was breathtaking for me, a founder of a Latina youth arts education, as well as many of my peers left behind in funding for DECADES while serving some of the city's fastest growing and diverse audiences. I think the city's economic development should continue the campaign that was started. Over $30M has been given to White led, White serving arts organizations just since 2010 as compared to $5 for Latinos a menial $1-2M for Black led, serving organizations - all the while the Black and Latino community being the center of Austin's coolness, even still while it gets more gentrified - people are drawn to the culture that was there and its remnants. These White led, mostly male boards providing services only afforded by Whiter, richer audiences have had decades - some 30-40 years to develop new earning strategies, grant attainment. These groups have development departments while my own organization, impacted by the deficit in equitable funding, just got a development director in 2019 for the first time in nearly 20 years. That was not without trying and hustling!  I founded Latinitas and it has been able to meet capacity needs because the city took the time to acknowledge groups like ours doing so much for so little. Over 40,000 girls and teens in Latinitas have experienced filmmaking, writing, podcasting, graphic and web design and other STEAM activities. They are Austin's biggest youth population, but also most marginalized.

